My roommates and I call it the Daikoke's for short--yeah, that's how often we speak of it. Despite it being in Little Tokyo (which is a bit away from Westwood, where I live), this has got to be my most frequented restaurant during my four years of living in LA. If you've had Japanese ramen before, then you're really going to appreciate the quality of this bowl. If you've never had Japanese ramen, then you're still going to think it's delicious, but you might not be able to appreciate how good Daikokuya actually is. IT'S OKAY THOUGH, give it another try in a couple of weeks or months and let that back fat really sink in next time. Oh yeah, ALWAYS get the back fat (Kotteri) because it makes your ramen that much more savory. The menu is pretty simple. It seems like they are very stringent on the experience they want their customers to have. They offer one bowl of ramen. Everyone gets to eat the same thing and you have the option of adding that back fat (Kotteri) that I mentioned. You can also get a combo meal, which is that bowl of ramen plus another small rice bowl of your choice (i.e. Chicken & Egg, Fried Rice, Eel, and several more). If you order a combo, you also get a small salad bowl as an appetizer. It's pretty much just shredded cabbage with thousand island sauce, but I love it. I would order the combo just to get the appetizer, but that's just me. Now, if you ordered a combo and want to make the most of your meal, I suggest not touching the small rice bowl at all. You will not have room for it! It makes a good breakfast or lunch for the next day and I usually have mine packaged to-go. The only bad thing I have to say about Daikokuya is the wait. It's a tiny place and you should definitely come with a large party. (A party of four is just large enough to avoid getting counter seats, which you might want to avoid.) Expect to wait! It actually makes you hungrier, which makes the ramen taste even better. There is a way around this, though: go right before closing! It closes at 11pm, 12am, or 1am, depending on the day, so get there 15-30 minutes before it closes and the wait will be significantly less (15 minutes vs. the usual 1-2 hours). If you do happen to go during primetime, there's a nice bar just down the street and a good ice cream/mochi place in the village plaza across the street if you're interested. Enjoy!
