Ramen..ramen...ramen......Probably in the top of the list of ramen noodle places anywhere. Took the entire family, plus a friend to a Little Tokyo field trip on a Friday afternoon. Looked over a Diakokuya and saw no more that 4 people in line outside. So.....we said.....Lets take advantage of the relatively short line......so we did. Waited for about 20 mins and boy.....it was sure worth it! The place is small, probably easy to miss, but it may very well be the only one on First Street with a Yellow awning outside. So......look for that. Inside, it is relatively a decent sized place....if there are only a couple of you in your group, take the bar, you might have better luck getting seated earlier. We ordered the Daikokuya Ramen Combinations.....let's talk about them in general.....SHEESH!!! Unless you are starving to death, those combinations are a lot of food!!! We had the following combos, Tuna Sashimi, Katsu-donburi, and Tempura. All were pretty good! The combos start with a nice light salad of shredded cabbage, carrots with a creamy ginger, sesame, soy dressing. They give you a good sized portion of it too. The tuna was fresh although the rice was a tad over vinegar-ed for me. Too much tang. I like it just seasoned enough to highlight the freshness Êof the fish without masking any of its faults. The katsu-don was really good. Perfectly seasoned and not too salty, the katsu was well cooked and not greasy. The tempura was really good. Nice cluster of sweet potatoes, carrots, onions and one shrimp. Now.....for the Ramen itself. I cannot say enough good things about it. Every detail of the bowl was perfection. They really know their Ramen bowls!!! The broth was heaven, rich but not too heavy, I can only imagine a big pot with soup bones simmering in it, extracting their goodness to make this wonderful meal - Perfectly seasoned, not much fat floating on top.....just perfect broth! The noodles.....cooked to a perfect ramen-al-dente. Firm with enough give for that nice tug...slurp after slurp. Even the egg was excellently cooked with just a touch of runny-ness in the yolk. If I had anything negative to say, probably the slices of meat.....although nicely seasoned and cooked, they had to use pork belly which was too fatty for me. I'd give it 4.5 stars!.......but then, I got the bill and for about $15 per person (after tip) I had to give it 5-stars as we burped our way to the Japanese Village Plaza!!!
