Wow. So lately I've been on a journey to taste all the really notable ramen places in the LA area. I've gone to this place several times since last year, when I had tried it for the first time. Now that's a testament to how amazing this ramen join is. They really only have "one" type of ramen in soup, their Tonkotsu Ramen. They do have "dipping" ramen which is ramen that is separated from the soup that's used as the "dipping" sauce... or something like that. I haven't actually tried it yet. It must be good, but to be honest, when I want ramen, the ramen I would want is ramen in soup. Anyway, the fact that they base their business solely on the Tonkotsu Ramen shows how wonderful this dish actually is. You also have the option of using a richer, fattier broth for the soup called "Kotteri," which I always get. I mean... I'm still young. I can handle it. My most recent visit I ordered the combination meal of Tonkotsu Ramen Kotteri-Style with a Shredded Pork Rice Bowl. The meal is started off with a salad. I don't really the kind shredded veggies they use, but the good dressing makes up for it. Although I thought that the shredded pork would be synonymous with the pork belly rice bowl at other ramen joints, this rice bowl came out really well. I kinda wish they didn't put the candied ginger on top of the bowl, though, but that's just me not liking ginger. I just take it off though, problem solved.. Now onto the ramen. The soup base is amazing. Downright flavor packed in every spoonful. It's not too salty either, which many ramen joints tend to head towards. Their chashu pork that comes in the ramen is nice and tender, almost melting in your mouth. That's how good chashu pork in ramen is supposed to be. There are ample veggies, too, that make for a balanced meal that won't overwhelm the rest of the ingredients in the bowl. The ramen is nice and perfectly chewy, although they seem to use a different kind of ramen noodle than other places. The only quip I have is that the egg they serve with it tends to be overcooked and becoming hard-boiled. A really good ramen egg should be soft-boiled, with the yolk still very moist and almost runny. I wish they had it like that here. Overall, every single dish was really good. And the portions were huge. After finishing the ramen, I had to take the rest of my rice bowl to-go. In terms of the price, which came up to be around $12 for my combination, it's definitely worth it. The worst part of all this is that you will have to wait a bit at almost any point in time during the day. I've gone during dinner time as well as like 11 or 12AM in the middle of the night, and either way I'd have to wait from 10-30 minutes (I heard other people have waited longer...) to get a table. On the bright side, a lot of people don't end up waiting the whole time and just leave, thus making it faster for you, so don't lose hope when you see all those names on the clipboard! Parking is street parking, but I've always been able to find it, if not on the street it's on, then at the street over where the rest of Little Tokyo is located. THEY TAKE CREDIT CARD TOO! This place is one of the best ramen places I've gone to so far, on par with the likes of Santouka ramen. Yes, this place is amazing. On a side note, I love the descriptions on some of their menu items. For the chicken egg rice bowl, they describe the dish as "Reuniting mother and child in a soy sauce marinade over a bowl of rice." How depressingly delicious-sounding.
