Like most Yelpers believe, this was indeed, one of the best ramen I have ever had. I tried Daikokuya twice and finished the whole helping twice (and that rarely happens since ramen makes me full easily). I gave Daikokuya a score of 4/5 just for food. I'm not going to rate them on the facility or waiting time or service. But just a brief summary on those: facility was quite small which accounted for the extremely long waiting time (waited about 45 minutes for 2 seats at the bar) but it did give it a mysterious "hole in the wall" type of atmosphere; service was exceptional once you're seated even when they are busy - they get your drinks, take your order, and check up on you in a timely manner. Now to the food--both sittings I ordered the Daikokuya ramen which consists a broth created through the boiling of pork bones and other ingredients (so it is all handmade), ramen egg noodles, slices of pork belly with just the right amount of fat, flavor, and texture, a boiled egg, bean sprouts and other veggies to go along with it. Not sure why it is but all these ingredients into that flavorful broth is not too rich that I get full early and not too dull that I get bored of the flavors. Instead, it is the perfect combination and the right amount that concludes in me finishing it off with the feeling of complete satisfaction in the end. The bamboo shoots and bean sprouts help create that balance in flavor so they are pretty necessary when you order the dish. My favorite parts would be the ramen egg noodles, which is the pretty texture and consistency; the slices of pork belly which has that wonderful section of fat to give it that meaty flavor, the boiling egg with the rich yolk still intact, and finishing it off with the broth. Mmmmmmm...... Of course, I wouldn't eat Daikokuya everyday because it would be a little bit too much. But whenever my friends and I are near Little Tokyo and have a major craving for Ramen, Daikokuya is the place to go. I had to subtract a star from the perfect rating of 5/5 because of the time. Even when we come early to put our names on the list, my stomach sometimes can't take that much long of a wait and I end up getting grumpy.
