My first ramen love and still one of my favorites. I wandered into Daikokuya - probably like quite a few others - after reading a Jonathan Gold write up of the restaurant in L.A. Weekly. Up to that point, when I had Japanese soup it was udon and if I had ramen, it came in a styrofoam cup or a cellophane wrapper. All that changed after my first bowl of soup at Daikokuya. The dense, pork flavored broth and the chewy, but tasty noodles were a world away from cup o' noodles. I was immediately hooked and quite a few years later, ramen remains one of my major comfort foods. I have visited Daikokuya dozens of times since then and it remains a favorite restaurant. I have tried the gyoza - decent wrapper, so-so filling. I love the pork cutlet bowl - tender pork, panko encrusted and quick fried, over rice with a fried egg on top. I have ordered the kichi-men, which has a unique, slightly sour broth, and the regular tsukemen. In both, cool noodles are dipped in the broth, rather than served in the soup. Both delicious. The side salad that comes with the combo meals - finely shredded cabbage topped with a little spicy mayo - is simple, but quite satisfying too. But it is the Daikoku ramen that I go to Daikokuya for and it never disappoints. I like it "kotteri" style, with the broth denser and richer from extra pork goodness. Kurobota chashu, bean spouts, bamboo shoots, scallions, a marinated boiled egg and sesame seeds round out the bowl of soup and noodles. I usually add a scoop of garlic, available at the table to spike up the flavor. The chashu is perhaps a little fatty and I tend to prefer a slightly thinker cut of pork, but that is a small quibble. ÊThe noodles are just average, but not bad. Portions tend towards the large size. A regular bowl of soup is quite large. The kitchen and the servers are friendly and efficient. Seating is in around 7 or 8 booths and at an L-shaped counter adjacent to the soup kitchen which allows you to watch the ramen makers at work while you dine. It can get a little hot, but that just gives you one more good reason to order a cold beer. The dining room is decorated with vintage Japanese signs and ads and a variety of Japanese music is piped in. After years of eating in the dining room, I find the setting very welcoming - revisiting a cherished spot. The downside? Be prepared to WAIT. Sometimes a LONG wait. ÊThere is a list of names at the door and the staff is pretty efficient in getting people in and out of the restaurant without ever making the meal seem rushed. However, the wait can seem endless when you are fiending for a bowl of ramen. Highest recommendation.
