Lotta red stars for this ramen house on average. The reviewers are basically right, this place serves up a one-two punch that edifies what ramen can aspire to in the noodle diaspora of the West. I reserve one star only because the wait can be discouraging. But certainly we've all waited a good time at popular eateries but if it's not fine dining, our expectation for food that is priced between the $7.50-$15 range is to be seated in under 40 minutes tops. But that's gastro-economical prejudice on our parts. It's small and maybe seats about 60 but the booths are first come-first serve and can be taken up by a couple who wandered in from Nova Scotia so if you're a small party or alone, the counter seat is your best shot. There is only one kind of hot ramen served here so your hungry mind isn't overwhelmed at a pointless array of ramen combinations that in some places include corn, seaweed, miso v. shoyu, chicken, mountain vegetables, bamboo shoots, or the kitchen sink. Like the fabled Chinese monks who perfect the single death punch all their lives, Daikokuya delivers a lethal single ramen with a miso colored, pork broth (boiled down from pork bones and shoyu) that is adorned with a hard-boiled egg that's marinated overnight and kurobuta (black pork) pork that is tender and fatty in the right amounts. For only $7.50, it is the steal of the City. If you're a control freak with fastidious tendencies, you can order the "tsukemen" Êversion which breaks up the component ramen parts into separate dishes: noodles in a bowl, broth in another bowl, and the rest in a final third bowl. You combine as you see fit in a ramenesque jigsaw wonder. If you're appetite allows it, do try their combinations. Ramen + fried rice. You'd think the ramen was all there'd be here but the other food is more than decent. Ramen + salmon roe bowl is one of my favs and even though it's an unlikely pairing, it somehow works. I also recommend a cold mug of Kirin on tap ($2). Why is Kirin beer so refreshing compared to Sapporo? Maybe they keep it chilled here to manufacturer's recommendations. I wouldn't put it past them here. And if you've ever been here and wondered what that white coffee-maker looking contraption with tubes coming out of it in the cook area is all about, it's their Kangen ionized mineral water system which either they use for cooking and/or as table water. Parking is not easy almost anytime of the day or night. I usually end up parking on Judge John Aliso St. Noodle up!
