ON SECOND THOUGHT: IT'S JUST OK The first time I went to Daikokuya, I was on a mission to have some ramen and was starving after a long drive from S.F. Under those circumstances, the meal I enjoyed there was really good but this time, I decided to try them again, having just ran through close to half a dozen other ramen-yas in the L.A. area and I wasn't starving. Revised opinion: It's ok but decidedly less impressive than the first time. (I've included my original review at bottom just so you can see how my opinion has evolved). For one thing, even though I didn't have to wait at all (the place only had 10 people in it), my broth was very warm but not exactly what you'd call "hot". I thought that was odd and frankly, "very warm" ramen isn't as fun to eat. Second, the broth is decidedly on the weaker side. It's not as plain jane as Asahi or Ramenya on the Westside but for a pork-based broth, I'd say it's less rich than Shinsengumi (which itself isn't that rich) and definitely far less salty, rich or enticing as what I just had at Santouka last week. Not to get all Tampopo about it but the broth is what it comes down to when you're talking about ramen addictions and in this case, it just tasted watered down a bit. The upside was that the pork is very good here. Fatty and flavorful and that helps impart more richness to the broth...or would have if the soup had been piping hot and therefore more likely to melt some of the pork fat. Also, I had forgotten that a bowl of ramen here costs $7.50 (basic, without add-ons). That's about $2.50 more than Asahi, $1 more than Santouoka, 50 cents more than Shinsengumi and $1 less than Chabuya. The size of their serving is probably somewhere between Asahi and Santouka. I didn't think it was overpriced (unlike Chabuya) but Daikokuya only cements my feeling that in terms of the best ramen, especially for the price, Santouka is the one to beat. Lastly, it must be said that Daikokuya is not that convenient to get into given its location in a high traffic, low parking (free parking that is) neighborhood. I happened to be downtown so I decided to cruise by but if I lived with 15 minutes of Daikokuya and 25 minutes of Santouka or Shinsengumi, I'd much rather spend the extra time and go to those other spots since I know that parking is far easier (plus, both places make better ramen). I have perhaps one or two more places to try downtown but I'm starting to become thoroughly convinced that if you want really good ramen in L.A., you have to head south. ***ORIGINAL REVIEW*** I went to Daikokuya after being shut out of three different ramen-yas in the Bay Area (because the wait was too long or they had closed out lunch already) and then driving six hours down to Los Angeles. By the time I got to Little Tokyo, I was famished at had ramen on the brain something bad. Under those circumstances, I might have been inclined to turn even a middling meal into something miraculous but given that I've been trying over half a dozen ramen spots over the last month, I had some semblance of an objective opinion about Daikokuya: It's a very good, satisfying and reliable bowl of ramen, especially for the price. The combos you can pair it with (I got tuna sashimi over sushi rice = awesome) elevate it even more. There's nothing I can really nitpick about eating there except to say that while it was very good, especially in my frame of hunger, it wasn't transcendent. Or, to put it simpler, it wasn't better than Santa Ramen in San Mateo or even Halu Ramen in San Jose. PLUS: The pork-based broth had a good richness to it but it could have been both a little richer and saltier to give it just a bit more punch. The noodles were also good but not memorably great. As noted, the combos are solid though and most of them are priced under $10. That's solid bang for the buck. MINUS: I had to wait even though it was well after 9pm. I shudder to think what it would have been like had I gotten there at 6 or 7pm instead. I didn't mind waiting 5-10 minutes. 30 minutes though? Doubtful. On the whole, I thought the food itself was comparable to Shinsengumi in Gardena BUT parking is easier at Shinsengumi and my gut feeling is that the wait wouldn't be as bad there either. Shinsengumi (as my review indicates) also has a great kids meal, something I didn't see at Daikokuya (or any other ramen-ya for that matter) so b/t the two, I'd have to give the nod to Shinsengumi.
