Decent. Just ok. Alright. These are the words that come to mind when I remark on my dining experience at Daikokuya. Try as I might and despite the glowing reviews here on yelp I simply cannot bring myself to giving this famous Ramen House more than three stars. Allow me to elaborate. I traveled to Daikokuya with the intention of Êspending a lazy early afternoon in Little Tokyo, which I did and enjoyed myself greatly. Getting to Little Tokyo around 11:28 and after parking and sauntering over to Daikokuya I was pleasantly surprised to see a nice little queue forming around the facade of the restaurant. After all, a line is a healthy indication of food worth waiting for and food worth waiting for is generally quite delicious. Generally. Stepping into Daikokuya is akin to stepping into a portal tied directly to a Ramen House in Kyushu. It's loud, cramped, hot and haphazardly decorated. Your given an almost 1940s era vibe from the fat bright red booths and wood planks that compose the interior. Faded signs in Japanese adorn the walls, massive lanterns do little to light the room but add to the closeness felt within the restaurant itself, The moment you cross the threshold you are greeted with a hearty irashaimase! and are told to promptly put your name on a list to be seated...there is always a list. What I did notice to be somewhat interesting was how when you are eventually seated at either the bar or one of a half dozen booths, your waiter will shout your name and a welcoming to the other waiters and cooks in the restaurant who will all immediately shout back welcoming you. A nice, personalized touch. Hearing nothing but fantastic things about their house ramen, the Daikoku Ramen, I ordered a bowl (Kotteri "flavor" uses more back fat in the tonkotsu broth) and once again for consistency sake added a side of gyoza to go with my water. I say this completely without hyperbole, the gyoza at Daikokuya are quite literally the best I have ever tasted. What is initially so compelling about them is that they are formed, if you will, to look more like rectangular pouches than the usual up crimped dumpling most think of when speaking of Jiaozi. They are prepared the same way, pan-fried after being boiled but just before they are finished, Êa generous helping of shoyu is dumped in to deglaze the pan. The immensely high heat sears the shoyu into a crispy like skin on the gyoza covering them in an extra layer of salty flavor. The ratio of pork to vegetable in the filling is balanced perfectly, melting succulently together with the dough to create a one of a kind dumpling experience. Their only detriment? They were covered, not garnished, COVERED with scallions. To get to the gyoza I had to mine through a mountain worth of the thinly sliced onion. An off-putting start to a meal to be certain. Speaking of green onions, allow me to guide the review towards the star attraction, the Ramen. I should have taken my mining gear with me. My ramen arrived piping hot and in a massive bowl. The broth gave off a sinfully rich smell and I was able to see the marbling of extra fat weaving in the creamy broth base. My eyes also made their way towards an obelisk of green onions, who's base was rooted with about 320,000 bean sprouts. I have little against green onions in general; I do not mind them in miso soup or lightly garnishing my ramen. I do mind when so many of them are piled up in the middle of my bowl that when I go to stir my noodles, they encompass every inch of the broth, making certain that with EACH BITE I will get that very sharp taste of onion. The excessive green onions nearly destroyed my ability to break down the flavor profile of the tonkotsu. Bean sprouts are generally rather flavorless so they are a perfect addition to a broth base as they provide wonderful texture and can soak up the stock all alone. Sadly the proportion of sprouts to broth was simply too massive and ended up, much like the green onions, encompassing every bite of the ramen taken. If I had to describe the Daikoku Ramen as anything I'd say it was more a wet salad than anything else. Yes the pork was delicious, albeit tiny in portion and what I could taste of the broth was smooth and fatty. The full soft boiled egg was also a fantastic addition as well. To say I was disappointed would be a somewhat of an overstatement. I went in to Daikokuya with tempered expectations, expecting to enjoy a lovely bowl of ramen. I did not enjoy my bowl of ramen however and that is why, despite all the charm of the location and the amazing gyoza starter, I had to give the relatively average score I have given. Daikokuya is without a doubt a fantastic experience, a true snapshot of an authentic Ramen Ya...but without the ramen to back it up I can't say I'll be thinking about the personalized welcome more than getting a fantastic bowl of ramen next time I get a craving.
