Best ramen place in LA, hands down. BUT and unfortunately, there is a but, the wait often takes a ridiculous amount of time. I've been here twice in the last year; the first time, my boyfriend and I had to wait about an hour and a half to finally be seated at around 8:30-ish. But although the wait was so long, it was totally worth it and I decided to come here in less than a second the next time I had a ramen craving. The second time, for a party of 4, we got there early (around 6?) and waited about 40 minutes. It's a tiny restaurant with space for about 8 booths and a bar that seats maybe 8-10 people. It's decorated with some old school Japanese movie posters, which fits the feel of the restaurant, right by that plaza in Little Tokyo. It's always busy, but not too hectic. My advice is to drop someone off there to make a reservation, find parking, then go hang out in Little Tokyo until it's about time for your number to be called. Have a mochi at Mikawaya (http://www.yelp.com/biz/É) across the street while you wait. Then head back over and get your big bowl of deliciousness. Their special ramen with a kotteri based soup is seriously the most savory thing ever. I've never tried their ramen without kotteri, and can't imagine why anybody else would. Health-conscious and scared of the fatty soup? Whatever, it's worth it. They also offer their kotteri ramen with the soup and noodles separated. This way, the noodles are at a cooler temperature, and you don't have to wait to dig in. I've tried this once and prefer it. I'm not sure of the proper way to eat it, but I crafted my spoonful of ramen noodles+bamboo and then scooped some soup to go with it in a perfect bite. I've also gotten the unajyu (unagi over rice) which is yum, as expected. Nothing crazy-amazing, but as expected delicious. I planned on taking a couple bites and taking the rest home for lunch the next day, but I left my leftovers on the table... :( I was sad about it for the entire week. Service is fast (they need to be to cater to such a large flow rate of customers) and food is served quickly, too. Nothing to say here. So seriously. The message you should get away from this review is: Go here now. In fact, I'll probably be coming here tomorrow, now that writing this review has made me want it ASAP. (I've never been here for lunch - I wonder if the wait time at noon is as bad as around 7?)
