When Drew and I were in LA we beelined here on Sunday afternoons. It was frigid and weird during the times we went, and the mere existent of Daikokuya got us out of bed. Steaming, hot broth, the smell of wok-fried rice, toasty, delicious green tea and nice servers in a cramped, tight space after waiting in the cold for nearly an hour. This is a most magical eatery offering only the most magical eating experience. This joint masters my three favorite things in life - handmade ramen noodles, katsudon, and fried rice. Yup. D and I are big fans of broth and noodles. the ramen here has this rich, salty, porky broth and perfectly chewy, long, handmade egg ramen noodles, and plenty of it. it's topped off with a few pieces of poached, flavorful, fatty pieces of pork and this amazing, braised egg where the white is cooked all the way through but the yolk is still a creamy, translucent yellow. And can't forget the abundance of green onions, that really give it the extra dimension of flavor. If this sounds magical, it is, and I haven't yet found ramen that sastisfies me like this anywhere in the US. Secondly, D and I have always been huge fans of the katsudon. We've been to a billion different joints in many different states that do it well, but none like this - you still get really crispy, lean, but JUICY thick katsu atop a bed of hot rice with softly, but thoroughly, cooked eggs, green onions, and sweet soy. The best bowl of katsudon we've ever consumed, and you can get a mini katsudon + ramen combo for like 10 bucks or something. Crazy. Third, I'm a bit of a fried rice whore. I lived in Korea as a youngster and became obsessed with koreanized/japanse Chinese food you can order and get delivered in a metal carry-out box. The fried rice here resembles the taste of those times, only better. It's perfectly seasoned, fried in a wok to perfection with nice pieces of pork, carrots, eggs, etc. The rice, to note, is always cooked to a perfection, and it's a wonderful accompaniment to my ramen noodle (the portion is rather generous for a small size - you can also get this as part of a combo with the ramen noodles if you wish). The service, while a bit scatter brained, is always dead on - they never skip a beat, and it's very friendly. The green tea is always delicious. I don't like to wait, but the wait is always worth the consistent quality of food and service, and I will make it a point to come back every time I am in town.
