A bowl of ramen at Daikokuya is around ten dollars and consists of heaping servings of intoxicatingly rich, milky broth seasoned with special shoyu; perfectly-boiled noodles; not enough bamboo shoots for my taste; a generous sprinkling of finely-chopped scallion; and a boiled egg whose magic is not only in its velvety, still-sort-of-molten yolk but also in the firm yet soft white whose color has been tinged with a slight brown and is utterly indescribable. The thin slices of tender chashu pork finishi off the bowl. This is not the Shin Ramen you boil up with its fiery, MSG-laden soup packet at midnight after a bout of drunken hunger pains strikes; it's sophisticated yet down-home; subtle yet flavorful; and good in every way. We also had a donkatsu appetizer, which we saw being fried for a second time and served immediately to us, still crackling from its oil bath and crunchy on the outside, firm, tall and buttery on the inside. The katsu is perfect, but we both wished that the dipping sauce had been more flavorful. Daikokuya runs a tight ship: everything is ready-to-cook when you order, like the katsu, which is pre-fried to speed up the service (it probably also contributes to the crispness of the batter). Still, on a typical night you'll have to wait just like everyone else who puts down their name on the waitlist and huddles around the small restaurant, hoping to get in. We waited for an hour on a Tuesday night, and it's impossible to get a booth if you're a smaller party. A party of two will likely be relegated to the counter, which is entertaining in that one gets to witness the food prep, but it can get pretty sweltering. But it was worth the wait and heat for the awesome ramen we had that night.
