This is easily the 2nd best ramen that I've had in the US (First being Ippudo). For comparison purpose, I've had ramen in Shinsengumi, Santa Ramen, Halu Ramen & Maru Ichi before. I haven't tried Santouka yet but it's because I've had it in Tokyo & it's available where in my home country (Singapore). For me, rating a ramen place isn't that hard. There should be 3 main categories: 1) Noodles, 2) Broth, 3) Meat and an optional 4th category for side dishes. Daikokuya's noodles are decent, nothing special. Their soup is fantastic. You can feel the fattiness of the pork and that it really has been boiled/cooked for a long time. And if you're a garlic lover like me, you'd love the minced garlic that they provide on the table. And...*drumroll*...The thing that sets Daikokuya apart from any other ramen places I've been to so far is their CHASHU. It was just out of this world. Super tender, right amount of fattiness and not dry at all. Some other stuff: 1) Their tsukemen isn't half bad either 2) We reached there by 11:30 on a Thursday night and there was still about 7 people lining up. I can't freaking imagine the queue on a weekend lunch/dinner time. And we were also the last person to be served, they had to reject a few other parties because they ran out of noodle. 3) I had the large portion and I'm wondering if they just use a bigger bowl and add more soup compared to their regular portion. The bowl looks bloody humongous but there really wasn't that much noodle/chashu in it, just some insane amount of soup.
