3.5 Stars, Rounded off to 4 Stars. Daikokuya displayed a C rating upon entry... but whatevers, I enjoy eating at Yatais in Japan & Night Markets in SE Asia. ÊI'm sure compared to the sanitation guidelines with regard to those places, a "C" in LA can't be too bad. Ê(I hope...) ÊHowever, I've read an actual LA County retail food inspection check list (easily accessible on-line) and learned to really appreciate the stringency of (basic) cleanliness and disease controlled practices they demand from restaurateurs in our community. ÊI sincerely understand that running a restaurant must be Êtough. ÊAnd coming here makes me a bit skeptical, as it sort of exudes desperation. ÊDesperation of it 'knowing' they need to shape up their rating, yet simultaneously needing to almost tread water to survive its demands, due to its popularity. And throw in the fact that they are confined in a small space, have no air conditioning and deal with downtown weather during the sweltering summertime. ÊWith all empathy, their world must be spinning! Ê Now with all the cleanliness factor aside, I'm giving this review based on merely their product and service. Ê I'm Tonkotsu (pork based) Ramen's hugest fan... I really was drawn to Êthis place because they stick to one style of ramen, but two forms of presentation. Êa.) served traditionally steaming hot in one bowl, or b.) tsuke-men style, basically same ingredients as the above, but everything pre-separated for you, including the noodles from the broth. I chose the tsu-ke men because I've never eaten ramen like this method before, but in the end, you end of mixing everything together anyways and it becomes sort of a nuisance. ÊThis tsu-ke men is probably great for those of you who like extra hard noodles, because this method maintains your noodles to remain hard throughout your meal, yet since they shock your noodles in cold water before serving, it does cool down your broth, resulting in lukewarm ramen. ÊI personally love my ramen 'burn your tognue' hot and should have ordered the regular bowl! ÊMy bad. Ê Broth - well, I could write a book about how I prefer my broth... different places have their signature styles. ÊI certainly enjoyed the broth as it wasn't too overpowering with pungent pork fat, nor too salty and had a nice, rich aroma. ÊNot the best I've had, but completely hit the spot. The noodles were a minor disappointment... while I appreciated the al dente hardness, I didn't really care for the flavor nor the consistency of the noodle. ÊI hands down prefer Shinsengumi's much, much more so. We shared the Fried Rice and that was actually excellent! Ê Service was extremely friendly and efficient... we got in just minutes before their evening rush. ÊBy the time we were leaving, a line had already formed outside. I recommend you visiting this place during off peak hours for a late lunch, or late night post drinking snack.
