After hearing the recommendations of a couple good friends and seeing that this place had over 600 reviews here on Yelp!, I decided that I absolutely had to give it a try. The verdict: It was good, but, personally, I think that the hype about this place has got to be a bigger deal than the quality of the famous ramen itself... Perhaps it was because everyone made such a huge deal out of it that my expectations were too high... So my friend and came here in the middle of the afternoon on a weekday in hopes of being able to get a table without having to wait for a billion years. Surprisingly when we arrived, the tables were all full so we had to wait a mere 2 mins before being seated. Wow... who would have thought that so many people would want to go to Daikokuya around 3pm on a weekday? The restaurant is pretty small... I'm guessing it seats only about 24 people in the 6 booths then about 10 on the counter stools. The decor almost reminds me of an old 1950's American diner feel if not for the Japanese posters and paraphernalia on walls and hanging from the ceiling. Ê Anyways, we both decided to get combination dishes of the famous Daikoku Ramen along with Chicken and Egg ($10.95) for her then Tempera ($11.50) for me. The waitress took our orders on a spiffy palm pilot type of device and was able to answer my questions easily. While waiting just a short while for our combos, we were given a small salad of iceburg lettuce shreds, onion and dressing... which wasn't exactly ideal since we both don't like and weren't expecting onion in there, bleh! Putting the salad aside, it was cool to watch the cooks preparing the ramen behind a counter in the dining room. The fact that they looked Japanese was reassuring, as well, that what we were anticipating was the real thing in being more authentic than other ramen we'd had before. The large, steaming hot bowls arrived at our table soon later, and we dove in. The broth, itself, is pork-based and light in flavor. Inside the soup are egg noodles, chashu pork, bean sprouts, a whole broiled egg, bamboo shoots, lots of green onions, and sesame seeds. As I said before, it was definitely good... but just not as good as the hype would make me expect. I think it's just because I'm just a fan of more flavorful broth and larger quantities of noodles, and this bowl didn't quite have those qualities. *shrug* Anyways, the pork was definitely melt-in-your-mouth texture, and the bamboo shoots were very flavorful as if they had been pre-marinated before. The tempera side order contained 1 shrimp, 1 thick onion ring, 2 green beans, and 1 slice of potato all over a bowl of rice. It was a bit small in quantity. but the flavor and consistency of the tempera batter was perfectly yummy. In the end, both of us took home leftovers of about 1/2 our ramen since we became quite full pretty quickly. One thing to take note of us how customer-friendly yet confusing their system is for paying the check. First, it was cool that they allowed us to split the check between 2 separate cards in which we indicated exactly now much we wanted charged on each card including tax and tip ($13.20 for her and $13.80 for me.) Upon receiving our receipts, I was surprised that the customer receives 2 receipts, each of which shows the supposed exact breakdown of the costs of the base, the tax, and the tip of both the total and then our individual subtotals. However... the numbers didn't really match up since it indicated that my base pay was the average of our 2 dishes and then I over-tipped... whereas for my friend (who ordered a less expensive dish), her receipt shows the same averaged base pay and that she under-tipped. Errr, confusing... I know. But whatever, we were correctly charged the amounts that we indicated regardless of the number breakdown shown on our receipts.
