Let's make this clear. I love ramen. I've made it a personal goal to try as many of the most talked about noodle places in the state. So let's get down to it, my friends and I were on a roadtrip and we heard from our socal friends that this place was one of the best in the downtown LA area, so we headed there as fast as possible. Surprisingly traffic from Westwood to downtown was good, but parking was not. I'm not going to complain too much about it, but simply it was 2 blocks off (street parking sucks). When we got there, the place looked really busy and we were right, there was a waiting list. We signed out names and we waited...outside...in the cold...for almost an hour and a half. Anyway to cut down to it, we finally got seated after closing hours and we all ordered the special, which at the time was the daikokuya bowl, with a side salad and a side entree. I ordered mine bowl with "extra richness" and got ungai over rice for my side entree. The salad was some simple greens topped with what seemed like thousand island infused with some wasabi, it was alright. The Unagi rice bowl was a different story. Imagine a normal bowl of rice...hidden by thick pieces of unagi. Simply from the looks of the dish I could tell the Unagi would be full of flavor, if it weren't for the bowl of ramen that was sent right out following out side dishes, I would've ordered another of those. Immediately as the soups closed in you could really sense their presence simply by the aroma. To top it off the soup was just as amazing; the portion was very generous for the price and it came with a soft boiled egg, strips of pork belly and some veggies. The meal seemed well worth the wait... up until the point when I started to slow down and noticed that I just found out what the "extra richness" was. As my soup settled from me not disturbing it, I noticed these tiny little globules coagulating at the service, I realized that these were the "extra richness!" An extra serving of fat and lipids straight from the broth stock before straining no less. It was an interesting sight and from that point on I stopped drinking the soup with my noodles, too bad though it was good, getting the dish w/o the extra addition tasted just as good as mine, less rich, but barely noticeable. Overall, this ramen house made it to perhaps my top 10 in cali and top 5 in socal. The ambience was really nice and reminded me of a cute little shop I found outside Tokyo once, the staff was very friendly after an obviously grueling day and the food was delicious! The only downside I could see is that this location has poor parking and the wait made the food almost not worth it, but the whole meal just happen to be worth the wait, but if we weren't as dedicated to try this place, we would've left and tried somewhere else. Stop by this place if you're in the area and are craving noodles try to follow this game play though; jot your name down, go check out the Japanese plaza and stores surrounding the area and come back in about 20 - 30 minutes and get ready to eat!
