I am not sure how to write to this review without coming off sounding like an overzealous ramen fanatic or perhaps even a ramen snob so let me apologize in advance. Ê First off I want to clarify that this review is strictly for the quality of the food. ÊThe service was fine and the "experience" was not much different from any other ramen place I've been to aside from the 1 hour wait to get our food. Ê As for the food, I am simply bewildered by the reviews here. ÊYes, the ramen is better than most ramen places in LA but I don't see how that, in and of itself, warrants anything higher than 3 stars. ÊThe way I see it, they get a star for attempting to make tonkotsu (pork base) ramen and another star for making it less than $10. ÊThey lose two stars for not sufficiently flavoring the base. ÊTo be honest it really seemed like they didn't add any flavoring () at all. ÊThey lose another star for using those ungodly thick noodles (sorry, I prefer Hakata style, thin noodles with tonkotsu ramen). ÊThen of course they lose another star for making me wait in line and getting my hopes up. ÊSo actually, by my math, 2 stars is kind of generous and frankly even if there were no wait I still wouldn't recommend Daikokuya to anyone who's ever had good ramen. ÊI guess to survive in the ramen wasteland that is LA, it's probably better to not know what good ramen really tastes like. Ê Let me reference this by saying that I lived in Tokyo for a year and during that time had ramen about once or twice a week at more places than I can count so I know what authentic ramen is supposed to taste like and Daikokuya is definitely not it. ÊI don't think the restaurant would last more than a week in any major city in Japan. ÊDon't get me wrong, I had plenty of bad ramen in Japan as well, but nothing quite as far below par as Daikokuya. ÊMy wife, who grew up in Japan, was equally disappointed and it is safe to say that we will not be returning. ÊLet me also reference this by saying we brought back wi